2.363 .236(Pointer to Member Cast Issues)J
41 164 :M
.425(Introduction)A
41 188 :M
f0_12 sf
-.101(There are two related pointer to member cast issues which have not yet
been resolved.)A
41 212 :M
-.11(The first is casting across virtual inheritance; that is, casting a
pointer to member such that the class of)A
41 224 :M
-.079(the pointer to member is virtual base class, or virtually derived from,
the previous class.  The current)A
41 236 :M
-.053(working paper requires this to work, and some compilers support it.  But
it\325s potentially expensive,)A
41 248 :M
-.09(and it makes pointers to members larger than they would otherwise need to
be.)A
41 272 :M
-.105(The second is casting to a base class of the class containing the
original member.  The ARM was)A
41 284 :M
-.036(unclear on whether this should work.  The issue was discussed in
94-0101/N0488 and at the)A
41 296 :M
-.091(Kitchener meeting.  Although there was considerable support for allowing
this cast, it was clear that)A
41 308 :M
-.054(the issue had not been discussed enough for a vote.  Since the existing
wording was unclear, the)A
41 320 :M
-.09(committee voted to clarify the wording in a way that did not support the
proposed casts, pending)A
41 332 :M
.13 .013(further discussion.)J
41 368 :M
f1_12 sf
3.168 .317(Virtual Base Classes)J
41 392 :M
f0_12 sf
-.096(In the following program:)A
76 416 :M
f3_9 sf
-.5(struct B { void f\(\); };)A
76 438 :M
-.498(struct D : virtual B { };)A
76 460 :M
-.515(void g\(D *d\) {)A
112 471 :M
-.489(void \(D::*pf\)\(\) = &B::f;  // implicit downcast)A
112 482 :M
-.493(\(d->*pf\)\(\);               // call)A
76 493 :M
(})S
41 516 :M
f0_12 sf
-.111(The call through the pointer to member must, using only information
stored in the pointer to member)A
41 528 :M
-.102(itself, cast the pointer \322d\323 from \322D*\323 to \322B*\323, in
order to provide the correct \322this\323 parameter for B::f.)A
41 540 :M
-.116(Of course the relative position of B to D isn\325t fixed, since a class
derived from D may place B at a)A
41 552 :M
-.038(different offset.)A
41 576 :M
-.103(So pointers to members must contain enough information to perform this
upcast; this makes them)A
41 588 :M
-.084(larger than would otherwise be necessary.  And when a pointer to member
is dereferenced, the code)A
41 600 :M
-.078(must check whether to do the upcast \(it isn\325t always needed\), and
perform the upcast if needed.  )A
41 624 :M
-.118(The check and the upcast can sometimes be optimized out if there are no
virtual base classes.  The)A
41 636 :M
-.098(memory for the description of how to upcast cannot be optimized out,
since it\325s possible to declare a)A
41 648 :M
-.109(pointer to member using a incomplete class.)A
40 681 486 25 rC
199 702 :M
