f0_12 sf
-.134(The problem is even worse with indirect virtual inheritance:)A
58 56 :M
f3_9 sf
-.504(struct V { int a; };)A
58 78 :M
-.498(struct X : virtual V { };)A
58 100 :M
-.498(struct Y : virtual X { };)A
58 122 :M
-.49(int X::*pxa = &V::x;  // implicit downcast)A
58 144 :M
-.49(int Y::*pya = pxa;    // implicit downcast)A
23 167 :M
f0_12 sf
-.093(The \322pxa\323 pointer to member contains a description of how to cast
from X* to V*.  The second)A
23 179 :M
-.081(implicit downcast must somehow modify this description so that it works
for casting from Y* to V*.)A
23 203 :M
-.104(This is a potentially expensive operation.)A
23 227 :M
-.082(There are two common implementations of virtual base classes.  In the
design used by cfront, derived)A
23 239 :M
-.086(classes contain pointers to their virtual base classes.  So the
description of how to cast to a virtual base)A
23 251 :M
-.109(must be the offset to the virtual base pointer within the derived
object.)A
23 275 :M
-.099(The second downcast must somehow map the offset to the V locator within
an X object to the offset to)A
23 287 :M
-.11(a V locator within a Y object.  There is no simple relationship between
these two offset values.  All the)A
23 299 :M
-.071(compiler knows is that the offset value in pxa is one of the virtual
base offsets in X.  For each of these)A
23 311 :M
-.061(offset values, there is a corresponding offset value in Y.  But there is
no simple mapping.)A
23 335 :M
-.15(One implementation actually generates a helper function containing a
switch statement which switches)A
23 347 :M
-.061(on the old offset, with a case for each possible value, and returns the
corresponding new value.  All)A
23 359 :M
-.121(this to implement what appears to be a simple static cast.)A
23 383 :M
-.102(In the other common design, each object \(of a class with virtual
bases\) contains a pointer to a table of)A
23 395 :M
-.1(offsets to the virtual base classes.  The content of these tables depends
on the actual relative positions)A
23 407 :M
-.105(of the virtual base classes in the complete object.  So like virtual
function tables, they must be)A
23 419 :M
-.107(initialized by the complete class and their contents are not known to
the class which uses them.)A
23 443 :M
-.108(In this model, each pointer to member contains an ordinal within the
virtual base class offset table for)A
23 455 :M
-.106(the member\325s class.  Once again these ordinals must be mapped when a
pointer to member is cast)A
23 467 :M
-.098(across virtual inheritance; but since the ordinals are dense, a simple
mapping table suffices.)A
23 491 :M
-.138(With either implementation, there is extra space in the pointer to
member and extra overhead for)A
23 503 :M
-.105(performing a simple static cast.)A
23 527 :M
-.086(Is this feature important enough to justify the overhead?  I suggest
that it is not.  I propose that pointer)A
23 539 :M
-.117(to member casts across virtual inheritance be ill-formed.)A
23 575 :M
f1_12 sf
2.971 .297(Upcasts Beyond the Member\325s Class)J
23 599 :M
f0_12 sf
-.073(Central to the concept of polymorphism in C++\312is the ability to store
a pointer to any of a set of)A
23 611 :M
-.088(concrete object types in a pointer to a common more abstract type, i.e.
a base class.  In the general)A
23 623 :M
-.085(case, this concept does not extend to pointer to members.  But in an
important specific case it does.)A
23 647 :M
-.103(In many situations it is useful to construct a pair consisting of an
object pointer and a pointer to)A
23 659 :M
-.115(member which can be dereferenced with that object.  This pair represents
a deferred action on the)A
23 671 :M
-.087(object, and so is a very convenient form for handling callbacks, remote
procedure calls, container)A
22 680 486 26 rC
