.318 .032(classes, etc.)J
41 56 :M
-.094(There is a natural representation of a hierarchy of such pairs, namely
the class hierarchy itself. It)A
41 68 :M
-.095(should be possible to cast the pair up to a base class, and dereference
the pair in the context of the base)A
41 80 :M
.136(class.)A
41 104 :M
-.099(There is no problem casting the pointer half of the pair up the
hierarchy to a base class.)A
41 128 :M
-.094(But when we try to cast the pointer to member half of the pair, we hit
some limitations.)A
76 152 :M
f3_9 sf
-.515(struct A {  };)A
76 174 :M
-.493(struct B : A { virtual void f\(\); };)A
76 196 :M
-.493(struct C : A { virtual void g\(\); };)A
76 218 :M
-.532(void h\(\) {)A
112 229 :M
-.491(// base class pointer to derived object)A
112 240 :M
-.507(A *objptr = new C;)A
112 262 :M
-.489(// base class member pointer to derived member)A
112 273 :M
-.49(void \(A::*memptr\)\(\) = \(void \(A::*\)\(\)\) &C::g;)A
112 295 :M
-.496(// ... handled as a pair ...)A
112 306 :M
-.49(// ... eventually dereferenced as a pair ...)A
112 317 :M
-.504(\(objptr->*memptr\)\(\);)A
76 328 :M
(})S
41 351 :M
f0_12 sf
-.122(Many compilers do not completely support upcasting a pointer to member
beyond the class containing)A
41 363 :M
-.09(the original member, i.e. to a class that does not contain or inherit the
original member.  There is no)A
41 375 :M
-.118(conceptual problem with such a cast; after all, we cast the object
pointer to a class in which the)A
41 387 :M
-.128(member did not exist either.  Yet the member is still there; it simply
isn\325t visible using the static type of)A
41 399 :M
-.059(the pointer.)A
41 423 :M
-.11(Similarly, when a pointer to member is upcast beyond the class containing
the original member, it still)A
41 435 :M
-.103(refers to the original member.   It should be possible to dereference
the pointer to member with an)A
41 447 :M
-.113(object which contains the member.)A
41 471 :M
-.116(When an object pointer is downcast, the author of the code must be
certain that the object really is of)A
41 483 :M
-.083(the derived type.  Similarly, when a pointer to member is upcast, the
author of the code must be)A
41 495 :M
-.118(certain that any dereference of the pointer to member is done with an
object of the derived type.  In)A
41 507 :M
-.126(both cases the cast must be explicit because it is impossible to
statically check its validity.)A
41 531 :M
-.115(In the special case of upcasting a paired object pointer and pointer to
member, it is easy to verify the)A
41 543 :M
-.107(program\325s validity because the pointer always refers to an object
suitable for use with the pointer to)A
41 555 :M
-.052(member.)A
41 579 :M
-.103(This is a very useful technique, largely because of its implicit safety.
 Although there are alternatives,)A
41 591 :M
-.094(they are not as clean and simple as this more obvious technique.)A
41 615 :M
-.089(How difficult is it for compilers to support these upcasts?  It\325s
trivial - because they already support)A
41 627 :M
-.138(them.  If a pointer to member is sufficiently general to handle multiple
inheritance and virtual)A
41 639 :M
-.065(functions, it is already general enough to handle the proposed
